10,000 美元，巴里。</p><p> RITHOLTZ：这在 70 年代是一笔巨款。并不真地。</p><p>摩根森：不，不完全是。</p><p> RITHOLTZ：这在 50 年代甚至不算大钱。我的意思是，一年10块钱根本不算什么。这就是您对华尔街产生兴趣的原因吗？</p><p>摩根森：是的。所以我对自己说：“我没有一个富有的爸爸。我没有一个有钱的丈夫。我得自己做。那么我能做什么呢？</p><p>大约在那时，华尔街正在与平等就业机会委员会就性别歧视案件进行斗争。他们没有在街上雇佣足够的妇女。这是我们正在谈论的 80 年代初期。</p><p> RITHOLTZ：嗯，谢天谢地，问题已经解决了。</p><p>摩根森：是的。</p><p> RITHOLTZ：现在我们在金融领域实现了性别平等，谢谢。</p><p>摩根森：嗯，不完全是，但比以前好多了。反正…</p><p> RITHOLTZ：嗯，这绝对更好。</p><p>摩根森：所以他们必须开始雇用女性，因为他们输了这个案子。于是，我向大型经纪公司申请了推销员的职位——当时是添惠、美林、保德信……</p><p>里索兹：对。</p><p>摩根森：我在添惠公司找到了一份工作。我得到这份工作的原因是因为我在电话测试中失败了。</p><p>里索兹：真的吗？嗯，你之前做过一些新闻工作，所以你不害怕向人们提问。</p><p>摩根森：是的。</p><p>里索兹：对。</p><p>所以，现在是 80 年代，在巨大牛市的开始阶段，并不是 82 年的任何人都知道，接下来的 18 年将是一艘火箭飞船。</p><p>摩根森：等等，等等，等等。当我坐在 Dean Witter Reynolds 的椅子上时，道琼斯工业平均指数为 781 点。</p><p> RITHOLTZ：仍然低于 1,000。简直不可思议。</p><p>摩根森：是的，顺便说一句，这使得出售股票变得困难，因为人们仍处于回顾阶段。</p><p>里索兹：当然。</p><p>摩根森：他们没有期待。但是，1982 年 8 月——你还太年轻，不记得那件事……</p><p> RITHOLTZ：哦，不，我对此记得很清楚。</p><p>摩根森：轮到的时候。有点像，“好吧，股票太便宜了。这就是你想去的地方。”</p><p> RITHOLTZ：当时是 7 PE，对吧？</p><p>摩根森：是的。标准普尔指数的 7 PE。你知道，那是一个转折点。所以，我确实为这一举动做好了准备。</p><p> RITHOLTZ：你在添惠公司待了三年、四年？你在那里待了多久？</p><p>摩根森：我呆了三年。我经历过 1983 年科技股的熊市，你不记得了，当时个人电脑正处于初始阶段，计算规模正在变得越来越大，而且它们已经远远超出了自己的预期。</p><p> RITHOLTZ：当时我们还称它们为科技股吗？那句话是什么？</p><p>摩根森：你知道，我不知道。我认为是科技股。反正…</p><p> RITHOLTZ：我根本不记得那个熊市。</p><p>摩根森：是的，情况很糟糕。这是恶毒的。那是 1983 年夏天。所以，我经历了惨痛的教训，当你向人们推荐的股票因为你的公司说它们将告别而下跌时，会发生什么，而那些人会赔钱。我感觉很糟糕。</p><p> RITHOLTZ：嗯，他们不是告别，只是在接下来的六个月里不会。那就是问题所在。</p><p>摩根森：你知道，他们超前了。欣快感、势头变得太疯狂了。</p><p> RITHOLTZ：1983 年有欣快感吗？</p><p>摩根森：是的，当然。</p><p>里索兹：不是开玩笑。</p><p>摩根森：哦，是的，Eagle Computer，我的意思是，其中一些东西是雄心勃勃的。因此，当你有客户打电话给你说，天哪，我所有的钱都去哪儿了？这对我来说是一个巨大的创伤。我真的感觉很糟糕，我有点觉得如果你有太多的负罪感，也许不适合做生意。</p><p> RITHOLTZ：（笑）这就是让你重新回到新闻行业的原因吗？</p><p>摩根森：这就是让我回来的原因。然而，我确实有，或者说我现在掌握了很多关于华尔街世界如何运作的信息。</p><p> RITHOLTZ：这正是我下一步要去的地方，你有找到华尔街一些不为人知的操作的诀窍。你整个职业生涯都在这样做。作为经纪人，让你了解“嘿，这东西到底是如何运作的？”有多重要？</p><p>摩根森：非常重要，巴里。我的意思是，正如他们所说，你真的看到了内部运作方式，以及香肠是如何制作的。因此，我会看到场外交易柜台、场外股票交易柜台将如何推动股票并鼓励经纪人出售它们，并在其中投入大量佣金，因为一些大卖家正在进入市场而移动它们。市场。</p><p>里索兹：对。</p><p>摩根森：这让我震惊，有几件事让我一直看到客户并没有被放在第一位。当然，还有我几年后写的那些相互矛盾的分析师。我亲眼目睹了这一点，我的客户也因此受到了伤害。</p><p> RITHOLTZ：所以让我们放一点阳光，让我们给这只猪涂一点口红。</p><p>到这里，已经是 40 年后的事了。街道的信托一侧在 80 年代很小，现在不仅很大，而且是增长最快的部分之一。虽然我们离性别平等还差得很远，但它肯定比以前更好了。</p><p>摩根森：现在比以前好多了，巴里。你不会让脱衣舞娘来参加人们的生日聚会，就像我当经纪人时看到的那样，好吗？</p><p>里索兹：难以置信。</p><p>摩根森：是的。我亲眼所见。</p><p>里索兹：我告诉办公室里的年轻人，去看《锅炉房》，去看《华尔街之狼》。这是真正的电影。铃声响起，那个世界就消失了。就像坏的部分一样，它消失了很好，但也有一些好的方面。就像培训项目一样，他们教人们什么是股票，​​什么是债券。他们曾经在大公司这样做过。与以前相比，这些现在就像小班一样。</p><p>摩根森：哦，真的吗，他们不再这样做了？</p><p> RITHOLTZ：他们这么做了，但不是原来的样子。因此，大约在您从华尔街转向新闻业的同时，杠杆收购热潮开始腾飞。它变得风靡一时。你当时在想什么？ “嘿，40 年后我要写一本书。”或者你是否在想，“这很有趣”，或者“问题来了”。当时你怎么看？</p><p>摩根森：当时，这看起来确实是对十年左右股票被低估的一个非常合理的反应。 20 世纪 70 年代，股市低迷。股票的死亡，你还记得那个封面。</p><p>里索兹：当然。 &#39;78，绝对。</p><p>摩根森：所以看起来这确实是对股市多年来被低估的一个相当合理的反应。因此，杠杆收购的初始阶段并不像现在那么有害，因为它们实际上接管了那些有价值的公司，坐在你可以看到的股价中，就像你提到的那样，七市盈率。</p><p>里索尔兹：是的。</p><p>摩根森：所以这确实是合理的。这是有道理的。这是之前发生的事情的自然结果。</p><p> RITHOLTZ：所以我们将更多地讨论《这些是掠夺者》这本书，但我必须提到你在书中真正关注的一系列名字。这些显然并不是私募股权的全部。还有很多，数百家其他公司。但阿波罗、黑石、卡莱尔和 KKR 似乎确实是焦点。是他们的规模、他们的行业、他们开展业务的方式吗？是什么让你找到了这四个人？</p><p>摩根森：嗯，首先是它们的尺寸，巴里。我的意思是，他们是这群人中的领导者。这些人和公司定下了基调，引领潮流。其他人模仿他们。 KKR 是 20 世纪 80 年代末 Kahuna 交易 RJR Nabisco 的幕后黑手。</p><p>因此，这是一群真正参与创建我们现在所说的私募股权的公司和人员。他们的规模和范围如此之大，以至于产生了巨大的影响。这就是我们关注它们的原因。</p><p>是的，有很多很多私募股权公司，但这些公司确实是定调的人。</p><p> RITHOLTZ：而且，您在书中提到了“门口的野蛮人”，该书重点关注 KKR 收购 RJR Nabisco。在当时，这有点不可思议，有人可以完全用低成本债务购买一家大型上市公司。这是否改变了比赛的走向？</p><p>一旦 RJR Nabisco 上场，是否意味着其他人也上场了？</p><p>摩根森：当然。</p><p> RITHOLTZ：这对接下来几十年发生的事情有何影响？</p><p>摩根森：是的。正如你所记得的，它也涉及国会。他们就此举行了听证会。我的意思是，当时这是一笔如此庞大的交易，确实让很多人感到紧张。有人研究过这些交易对工人和养老金意味着什么。这确实是质疑这些交易的影响的开始，但它们只是继续前进，继续前进。在 80 年代末，特别是在 1987 年经济崩溃之后，确实有一种感觉，我们真的不想插手此事。让我们让市场顺其自然吧。</p><p>事实上，我认为当时的财政部长说过，市场会解决这些问题，它们不会成为问题。</p><p> RITHOLTZ：市场最终总会解决这些问题，但这最终可能需要比预期更长的时间。</p><p>摩根森：是的。</p><p> RITHOLTZ：你提到他们产生了很大的影响，并且产生了很大的影响。他们还产生了大量的费用和大量的金钱。像 RJR Nabisco 这样的大型交易的金额是多少？</p><p>摩根森：嗯，当时听起来很大，但如果你现在回想起来，我不知道。我认为我们在书中有一个数字，可能是 7000 万美元或需要处理的费用。这甚至不是舍入误差。</p><p> RITHOLTZ：是的，这就是今天的零钱。</p><p>摩根森：这就是绕着钱走，对吧？</p><p>里索兹：对。</p><p>摩根森：所以，它变得非常非常大，巴里。随着市场和资本池变得越来越大。</p><p> RITHOLTZ：我们稍后会讨论，随着这些公司变得越来越大，华尔街也变得越来越大，而这在某种程度上却在下面造成了一个空白。但这真的非常非常有趣，看看这一切是在没有人真正想要很多这样的公司的时候开始的。是的，其中一些公司几乎已经死了。</p><p>所以你在这本书的开头就用了一句话让我很开心。 “让抢劫开始吧” 那么，让我们从这里开始吧。这一切从哪里开始，什么时候从“嘿，我们将帮助这些似乎无法获得融资的公司提供资金”转变为全面的盗版和抢劫？</p><p>摩根森：嗯，有几件事很早就发生了，你可以看到它们的开始。这些收购不仅是为了找到那些可能被低估或表现不佳的公司，我们还可以将它们塑造成型，然后将它们出售，当他们这样做时，当他们在监视它们时，当他们在关注它们时，精简它们，改善它们的运营，可以从这些公司中收取大量费用。</p><p>因此，首先，私募股权公司通常会派人进入公司董事会。有时，这些董事会成员身份将为这些董事会成员带来收入。还有一种叫做监控费的东西，即被私募股权基金或公司收购的公司必须向公司支付其监控、监督以及向公司提供的管理专业知识的费用。</p><p>现在这是有道理的，因为他们接管了公司。</p><p> RITHOLTZ：他们可以做他们想做的事，他们是所有者。</p><p>摩根森：另外，他们大概非常擅长管理，他们知道自己在做什么，并且他们的目标是稍后出售以获取利润。</p><p>里索兹：对。</p><p>摩根森：然而，监控费对他们来说确实有一种滥用的成分。它们通常采用 10 年期合同。因此公司同意在10年的时间内每年向私募股权公司支付一定数额的监管费。</p><p> RITHOLTZ：无论盈利能力还是他们的表现如何？</p><p>摩根森：哦，是的，不，这绝对是必要的。他们每年都这样做。</p><p> RITHOLTZ：最上面的一句话。</p><p>摩根森：因此，如果私募股权公司在五年后出售公司，公司仍然必须支付，仍然必须支付剩余的五年合同义务，即支付这些监控费用。</p><p> RITHOLTZ：现在，这不是吗？无论购买者是谁都知道这种情况正在发生，这不是会降低成本、购买价格吗？</p><p>摩根森：也许吧，但仍然如此。</p><p> RITHOLTZ：这是账面上的负债。</p><p>摩根森：但是，这仍然属于这些人。这是没有什么用的钱。</p><p> RITHOLTZ：成为国王真好。</p><p>摩根森：他们没有进行监控，但他们却获得报酬进行监控。</p><p> RITHOLTZ：还有其他类似的费用会破坏公司的稳定性吗？</p><p>摩根森：嗯，我想，我试着想，哦，好吧，好吧。嗯，首先，真正最终产生的巨额费用，这不是私募股权公司的费用，但许多此类交易的大问题是债务利息成本，好吗？</p><p>因此，当私募股权公司接管一家公司时，他们会给该公司带来大量债务。为了支付这些债务费用，其费用急剧增加。通常情况下，公司会提取——我的意思是公司——会以所谓的股利资本重组的形式提取资金。</p><p>他们会让公司背负沉重的债务，然后他们几乎会立即取出资金。这只是剥夺公司的一种方式——</p><p> RITHOLTZ：换句话说，当你说他们给公司带来债务时，他们就借了很多资本，所以现在公司拿着这笔现金，并承担了抵消负债，这意味着被收购的公司，以及 P/电子所有者/经理将从中收取费用。</p><p>摩根森：嗯，他们进行股息资本重组，这意味着他们将自己筹集的现金债务的一部分作为对自己的支付。</p><p> RITHOLTZ：谁把这笔钱借给了公司？</p><p>摩根森：可能是银行，可能是华尔街，可能是私人债务人，但它是——</p><p> RITHOLTZ：这通常也被证券化并出售到市场上？</p><p>摩根森：它可以是抵押贷款义务，现在是大额私人债务。但你已经有了这些股息回顾。 2007年，私募股权公司以股息资本重组的形式从公司提取了200亿美元。</p><p>里索兹：哇。</p><p>摩根森：到 2021 年，他们提取了 700 亿美元的股息资本重组。现在这是公司必须偿还的钱......</p><p>里索兹：对。</p><p>摩根森：为偿还它而筹集的债务。</p><p> RITHOLTZ：这并不涉及公司正在做的事情。</p><p>摩根森：它不会进入公司的运营，并且会产生与之相关的利息成本。</p><p>里索兹：对。</p><p>摩根森：这是我认为值得研究的另一个难题。所以，我们之前讨论过 RJR Nabisco。当你回顾 80 年代甚至 90 年代杠杆收购的历史时，你会发现它们似乎是很多鲜为人知、不一定面向消费者的公司、运输、物流和制造业。</p><p> RJR 是普通人最先知道的名字之一。</p><p>这种转变是如何发生的？大多数 80 年代杠杆收购的重点是什么？这些确实是非常不为人所知的事情。只是后来，或者至少在书中你是这样描述的，只是后来我们才知道它是家喻户晓的品牌、零售商和名字。如果你愿意的话，解释一下。</p><p>摩根森：嗯，我认为正在发生的事情 - 再说一次，我们之前讨论过一点，这些公司是被低估最严重的公司。</p><p>请记住，我们刚刚走出了一场非常严重的衰退。</p><p>因此，当时的工业公司可能受到经济衰退的严重损害。</p><p>因此，他们的市盈率可能低于标准普尔指数的平均水平 7。因此，这可能就是他们接管并更加关注他们的原因。</p><p>但同样，随着这种实践和过程演变成其他东西，它变得更多地与你所知道的一些大牌公司有关。</p><p>现在，一个重大的关键时刻是 90 年代初垃圾债券市场崩溃。这是在 SNL 危机之后。 SNL 被说服购买了大量垃圾债券。市场转向。米尔肯和德莱克赛尔·伯恩汉姆崩溃并失败了。</p><p>所以，这个巨大的垃圾债券做市商就消失了。垃圾债券市场真的陷入了困境，这也给从垃圾债券市场借款的公司造成了很大的困扰。现在这些公司的交易价格非常低。</p><p>因此，这些公司再次利用了这种困境。</p><p> RITHOLTZ：那么，你如何区分私募股权的杠杆收购品牌（有些人称之为秃鹫资本主义）与可信的中端市场银行业务和商业银行业务（实际上是这些中型公司为数不多的资本来源之一）考虑到华尔街开始追逐所有更大的公司？</p><p>摩根森：嗯，我认为开展这项业务有正确的方法和错误的方法。</p><p>当然，有很多公司在做正确的事情。至于这可能意味着什么，好吧，减少债务，好吗？对这些公司征收的债务可能非常具有破坏性。现在，巴里，我们正在经历一个利率上升的时期，公司正在经历困境，因为大部分债务都是浮动的。它不是固定的。因此，您需要记住的是，当利率为零时，公司借钱的相关成本与利率为 5 时是不同的。</p><p>所以这是这个难题的一个重要部分。那么，在这些交易中投入更多的股本而不是那么多的债务怎么样？在游戏中加入更多自己的皮肤怎么样？有点像一件事。</p><p>我认为经常发生的大规模裁员是非常有害的。我认为资产剥离也发生了，例如养老金被出售，资金过剩的养老金被出售，这些资金进入了私募股权公司而不是公司本身。</p><p>所以我认为你可以很容易地避免其中一些做法。当你把所有这些拼图都放在适当的位置时，你可能不会得到你所得到的回报。但我认为现在，我们必须考虑这个问题，解雇大量工人，剥夺养老金和健康福利，向这些公司征收债务，并且你想要五年后卖掉它们，你知道，这是我们在股票市场上经常感到遗憾的短期主义。</p><p>这真的是一种可以长期有效的商业模式吗？</p><p>因此，当私募股权在上世纪 80 年代和 90 年代真正兴起时，它本质上是一种机构配置。这不是夫妻间的投资。今天，情况发生了变化。它确实吸引了大量的零售资金。效果如何？</p><p>摩根森：嗯，你知道，这很有趣。正如你所说，多年来，几十年来，这是一种投资策略，仅限于成熟的投资者、高净值人士，以及能够接受这一事实的人，因为它是不透明的，它的费用很高，而且它并不完全是一种投资策略。就像投资标准普尔 500 指数股票基金一样，并不是那么简单。</p><p>里索兹：对。</p><p> MORGENSON：但现在它正在通过 401(k) 方式侵入夫妻店。唐纳德·特朗普领导下的劳工部确实为私募股权进入 401(k) 计划打开了大门。由于信托义务的理念以及这些文书的不透明性，这种情况以前曾被阻止或禁止过。</p><p>但是，是的，它开始渗透到我们所谓的高净值零售市场。其中 Blackstone BREIT 就是一个完美的例子。这是一家房地产投资信托公司，是 Blackstone 实体。</p><p>它在吸引高净值零售客户方面确实做了很多工作。我认为私募股权公司认为这是一个机会，因为他们并没有真正发展其业务的制度方面。养老基金的增长或许没有达到其需要的程度。因此，这对他们来说是一个成熟的市场。</p><p> RITHOLTZ：显然，401(k) 并不是分配领域中增长速度比直接福利或养老金快得多的部分，如果有的话，那就是街道的那一边正在急剧萎缩。</p><p>让我们来谈谈私募股权似乎正在涉足的一些新领域。这本书讨论了已经私有化的急诊室和急诊室。我一直认为急诊室和这类紧急服务是一种服务，是一种社区公益，而不是一种营利模式，我是否天真地没有意识到我们可以通过紧急情况货币化？还是应该将其排除在私人资产配置者手中？</p><p>摩根森：对于整个私募股权行业来说，这是一个非常非常关键的问题。现在，他们抓住了医疗保健作为一个巨大的行业，真正投入、投资。你知道这是为什么吗？因为它占国内生产总值的17%。</p><p> RITHOLTZ：对，巨人。</p><p>摩根森：所以这是一个非常非常大的潜在资金池。</p><p>因此，私募股权投资医生的业务，私募股权投资皮肤科业务。</p><p> RITHOLTZ：影像学、MRI、CAT 扫描，所有这些。</p><p>摩根森：麻醉学是另一大领域。是的，急诊科是另一个。医疗保健的困难在于你不应该将利润置于患者之上。</p><p> RITHOLTZ：那么，我们来谈谈医院吧。我不明白所有这些非营利医院是如何被收购并整合成一个以盈利为目的的非营利医院连锁店。这似乎违反直觉。</p><p>告诉我们一些那里发生的事情。</p><p>摩根森：巴里，我们真正讨论的是为医院提供人员的人才派遣公司。因此，私募股权不会购买急诊科。私募股权公司正在做的是运营急救部门。</p><p> RITHOLTZ：类似于酒店的运营方式。</p><p>摩根森：对于医院来说。就像任何人员配置一样，你知道，你是个大人物。你雇了一家人才派遣公司来帮你找人，好吧。因此，急诊科有两个主要参与者。一个是Team Health，另一个是Envision。 Envision 归 KKR 所有，Team Health 归 Blackstone 所有。</p><p>他们和其他规模较小的私募股权公司控制着全国 40% 的急诊部门。</p><p>哇，这么多。现在，当你去急诊室时你不知道这一点。医院雇用他们。当然，他们对医院说，我们将提高您的盈利能力。我们将帮助您赚更多的钱。他们会说改善病人护理。但我采访过的急诊医学医生表示，情况绝对不是这样的。</p><p>当私募股权公司进来时，他们会告诉他们如何开展业务。他们告诉他们如何为患者计费编写代码。</p><p> RITHOLTZ：嗯，他们是医学专家，不是吗，私募股权公司？他们不是有急救方面的专业吗？</p><p>摩根森：不，我认为他们在融资方面有专长。</p><p> RITHOLTZ：抱歉，他们是金融家。</p><p>摩根森：是的，他们在融资方面有专长。</p><p> RITHOLTZ：请原谅我的……</p><p>摩根森：并且回归。</p><p> RITHOLTZ：我必须告诉你，这太可怕了。我对私募股权进军房地产和其他领域没有意见，但急诊室似乎有点……</p><p>摩根森：是的，我的意思是，如果你谈论的是私募股权公司拥有的咖啡和甜甜圈，好吧。如果你不喜欢咖啡和甜甜圈，你就会去别的地方。但如果你需要一个急诊科，而这是你所在镇上唯一的一个，你必须去那里，而且它是由一家将利润置于患者之上的股权公司运营的，那就是一个问题。</p><p> RITHOLTZ：这种情况已经变得非常大，不一定是在大城市，而是在南方、农村地区，在医疗保健选择非常有限且缺乏医生的地方，并不是说可以选择说，“哦，我不喜欢西南将军。我要去东北综合医院，那是一个更好的急诊室。”</p><p>这通常是镇上仅有的游戏之一，对吗？</p><p>摩根森：当然。乡村医院确实受到了这种做法的打击。</p><p>另一件事，巴里，他们没有把名字写在门上……</p><p>里索尔兹：不。</p><p>摩根森：急诊室那边。他们没有说 Team Health 在这里，也没有说 Envision、KKR 或 Blackstone 正在运营这个项目。因此，请尝试查明您的急诊室是否由这些公司之一运营。这是非常难做到的。</p><p>再说一次，它是不透明的。同样，消费者并不知道这种情况正在发生。私募股权公司接管的大部分业务都属于秘密接管，因为他们不会把自己的名字挂在门上。</p><p> RITHOLTZ：那么我们来谈谈老年生活吧。敬老院什么时候成为利润中心了？告诉我们这一点。</p><p>摩根森：我认为这也许是最大的危机。这在 2021 年由芝加哥大学、宾夕法尼亚大学、纽约大学等学者进行的一项研究中确实变得非常明显，该研究研究了私募股权拥有的疗养院的长期死亡率，并将其与疗养院进行了比较。</p><p> RITHOLTZ：他们的效率要高得多，他们的死亡率也一定要低得多，对吧？</p><p>摩根森：他们的效率要高得多，因为也许他们雇佣的人更少来照顾居民，导致死亡率更高。</p><p>死亡率为10%。</p><p> RITHOLTZ：确实，这是一个很大的数字。</p><p>摩根森：10%，因此这些学者发现，他们所说的有 20,000 人因为在私人股本拥有的疗养院、护理设施中而丧生。因此，你会遇到学者们所说的情况，即重点，对成本削减的极度关注意味着更少的员工，意味着更少的护理，本质上转化为更少的护理。</p><p>这只是一项关于两者之间差异的引人注目的研究，他们将其与其他营利性疗养院进行了比较。所以这不仅仅是营利性与非营利性的对比。这是私募股权，营利性和非营利性的。</p><p> RITHOLTZ：在新冠疫情期间，私募股权医疗保健、老年生活、疗养院、急诊室、医院的表现如何？</p><p>摩根森：嗯，他们做得很好，因为他们从政府那里得到了很多《关怀法案》的资金。</p><p> RITHOLTZ：我的意思是，护理本身是如何进行的？疫情期间他们的表现如何？</p><p>摩根森：嗯，如你所知，医疗保健是一场灾难。部分原因是我们对流感大流行毫无准备。</p><p>巴里，我想说，我们毫无准备的原因之一是，自 2000 年代中期以来，医疗保健一直是私募股权的关注焦点。好的，HCA 就是一个完美的例子，这是一家通过杠杆收购私有化的公司。因此，这些公司再次专注于削减成本。</p><p>因此，他们不太可能储备个人防护装备、口罩，购买呼吸机，为大流行做好准备。而事实上……</p><p> RITHOLTZ：嗯，这些东西都是要花钱的。</p><p>摩根森：那要花钱。这是放在架子上的钱。这些人不喜欢把钱放在架子上。因此，国会实际上进行了一项研究，研究了如果我们经历一场大流行可能会发生什么。那是在 2005 年或 2006 年。它说：“我们需要储备更多设备。”</p><p> RITHOLTZ：2015 年，你对盖茨进行了研究，也说了同样的话？即时库存不起作用，因为在大流行期间你买不到东西。事实证明这是非常准确的。</p><p>摩根森：是的。但是，在 2020 年 3 月份整个世界崩溃之前的那些年里，在这之前的所有这些年里，我们的医疗保健在某种程度上正在耗尽，医疗保健公司也在流失，因为我们要减少成本，降低成本。 。</p><p> RITHOLTZ：所以，我现在要问你一个问题，但这也适用于保险，我们稍后会讨论这个问题。但联邦层面有监管机构。每个州都有一个医疗委员会。这种死亡率和健康状况都更差的医疗服务是如何盈利的，又是如何通过国家监管机构的监管的？</p><p>你可能会想象全州监管医疗委员会不会真正容忍这种情况。</p><p>摩根森：巴里，这是一个价值 64 万亿美元的问题，我希望您能问问每一位州检察长，例如，您为什么不追求营利性药品？</p><p>全国 30 多个州都有法规禁止所谓的企业医疗实践。这些法律在 100 年前就开始生效，当时江湖医生就在外面兜售疯狂的治疗方法。他们决定，这些州决定，你不能在病人护理之前获得潜在的利润。</p><p>因此医生实际上必须管理这些组织。据推测，这将避免将利润置于患者之上的问题。但非常非常非常少的州总检察长执行了针对企业医疗实践的法律。当他们确实带来案例时，它们是如此之小，如此简约，以至于他们向这些公司提供的产品甚至不是做生意的成本。所以就像，好吧，好吧，我会再做一次，下次甚至更大。</p><p> RITHOLTZ：那么我们来谈谈保险吧。保险单的内容​​似乎绝对令人震惊。私募股权投资是如何进军保险领域的？同样，这是一个受到严格监管的行业，拥有独立的、非常强大的全州监督小组和委员会。</p><p>保险界正在发生什么？</p><p>摩根森：嗯，我很想听你说它在州方面非常强大。</p><p> RITHOLTZ：至少它是这样呈现的。与试图获得保险业务许可的人交谈，或者在随后的诉讼中未能支付保单的人。保单持有人似乎有一些选择，特别是如果你有一位乐于接受的州长或州检察长，他们可以通过这些保险委员会施加压力，尽管也许我生活在过去。</p><p>摩根森：嗯，我认为情况参差不齐。我们只能说，有些州的监管很严格，但也有很多州的监管并不严格。</p><p>正如你可能猜到的那样，其中一些公司涌向监管更为简单的州。现在，保险公司被私募股权拥有的问题是，你可以理解为什么他们想拥有它们，因为这是一个资产池，这是一个他们真正可以产生巨额利润的资金池。它与银行不同，它不是快钱或热钱，它不太可能很快离开，巴里，就像我们在最近的一些银行问题中看到的那样。因此，对于这些公司、这些私募股权公司来说，保险公司确实是一个巨大的、非常稳定的资金池。这很有趣，因为在保险行业，你应该非常保守。我认为，大多数购买保险的人确实更希望他们的保险公司是一个保守的实体，它不承担风险，我们不会在这里摇摆不定。</p><p>您知道，是的，如果我可以获得更高的收益，那就太棒了，但我真的想知道在索赔时我会得到赔偿。</p><p>所以这些公司正在做的是购买这些保险公司，他们也在购买养老金资产，巴里，所以一家公司有养老金，比方说它是洛克希德公司、百时美施贵宝公司或几家公司。私募股权公司将购买这些养老金义务。</p><p>洛克希德或百时美施贵宝将其从账簿上删除，他们很高兴，他们转移了这些义务对他们造成的风险，而私募股权公司则接管了该风险。但现在，如果养老金失效，你就没有养老金福利担保公司为你提供支持。</p><p> RITHOLTZ：那么，一家公司可以通过将其出售给第三方来摆脱 PBG 的管辖吗？</p><p>摩根森：正确。这就是所谓的养老金风险转移，而且这种情况一直在疯狂地发生。私募股权公司是进行大量养老金风险转移的公司。</p><p> RITHOLTZ：这真的很有趣。</p><p>摩根森：所以，百时美施贵宝、洛克希德或库尔斯的养老金领取者是另一个真正依靠私募股权为他们的未来养老金、退休金、在需要时支付款项的人。</p><p>我认为，我们确实不了解其全部本质。不幸的是，我们将会看到，如果这些私募股权公司对保险公司的一些投资开始出现问题，我们可能会看到利率上升带来的一些问题。</p><p> RITHOLTZ：这些投资是否是公平交易，意味着您作为受托人代表养老金领取者进行管理。然后你就不能转身用你在街上卖的垃圾纸来装饰养老金吗？或者会发生这种情况吗？</p><p>摩根森：这确实发生了。现在，他们必须在向保险监管机构提交的法定文件中披露其在保险公司的投资组合中有多少是关联交易或相关股票、债券或抵押贷款等。</p><p>所以他们确实必须披露这一点，但我猜很少有人会阅读这些披露。</p><p>里索兹：非常有趣。我们来谈谈本世纪的保险交易。高管生活发生了什么？那里发生了什么？事情是如何偏离轨道的？</p><p>摩根森：《高管生活》是我们这本书的开头，因为它是一次巨大的失败，当然，它是在垃圾债券崩溃的时候发生的。</p><p> RITHOLTZ：但这之前是一家备受推崇的 AAA 保险公司。</p><p>摩根森：这是一家评价很高的保险公司。它的评价最高。</p><p>里索兹：一个优点。</p><p>摩根森：但它是由一个我们过去称之为枪手的人经营的。</p><p>里索兹：对。</p><p>摩根森：他是一个比一般保险公司高管更愿意冒险的人。他还从德雷塞尔购买了大量垃圾债券。当他们出售这些质量稍差的债券时，他是他们的顶级客户之一……</p><p> RITHOLTZ：质量稍差。</p><p> MORGENSON：不太知名的公司。他是来买东西的。</p><p>里索兹：对。</p><p> MORGENSON: So his firm, his insurance company, had a ton of junk bonds.</p><p> And when that market turned, it was dire for him.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: So this was really separate from private equity. This was just bad stewardship by an insurance executive who should be conservative. And, again, the question, where are the regulators when a conservative insurance company is buying junk?</p><p> I mean, it&#39;s right there in the name, they don&#39;t even hide it, junk bonds. What happened with Executive Life? They blow up.</p><p> MORGENSON: They blow up. The Department of Insurance for the State of California was, at the time, run by John Garamendi, who is now a representative in the House of Representatives from California, in Washington. And he was just brand new in the job. It was a new elected position. Prior to that, it had been appointees of the governor.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: You have to run to oversee?</p><p> MORGENSON: Yes, you have to run to the insurance …</p><p> RITHOLTZ: I don&#39;t see how that could go.</p><p> MORGENSON: Anyway, so he won the big job, and the minute he got in the door, junk bonds were cratering, and everybody was concerned about Executive Life, and would it be able to pay its policyholders. And so he seized the company. Now, keep in mind, Barry, that he seized it probably at or very near the bottom, okay? So junk bonds were starting to come back after he seized it. And so if it had been worked out another way, it&#39;s possible.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: Like just a re-org or a…</p><p> MORGENSON: Like a reorganization, it&#39;s possible that the policyholders might not have lost what they ended up losing.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: What was the haircut the policyholders get?</p><p> MORGENSON: You know, it&#39;s still to this day, we don&#39;t know, but it certainly is in the three or four billion dollar, maybe even higher.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: What percentage does that look like? A third, a half?</p><p> It was a big chunk though, right?</p><p> MORGENSON: It was a big chunk for many people. You know, I mean, I know of some cases where it was 40% haircut for some policyholders. It&#39;s very hard to, you know, getting numbers on this stuff, they really don&#39;t want to help.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: And then, tell us about the crazy rule that said, “Okay, now we&#39;re going to shred all the documents related to this.” What the hell was that?</p><p> MORGENSON: Well, okay. Let&#39;s just remember, this happened in 1991. The insurance department took it over in 1991. Then we had Apollo, Leon Black&#39;s new firm, after he flees from Drexel, the wreckage is burning at Drexel.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: Drexel collapsed.</p><p> MORGENSON: Drexel collapsed.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: Which arguably he didn&#39;t have anything to do with. That was mostly Milken&#39;s issue.</p><p> MORGENSON: No, he was not in the junk bond area. He was a corporate finance person. He was raising money for these companies.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: So, did he flee, or did he just say, “Hey, let&#39;s go launch our own company”?</p><p> MORGENSON: Yes, let&#39;s go launch our own company.</p><p>里索兹：对。</p><p>摩根森：是的。 But, I mean, it was obviously a dire circumstance. So, anyway, long story short, he ends up getting ahold of this huge junk bond portfolio, which was a lot of paper that he had put into Fred Carr&#39;s — that&#39;s the name of the guy who ran Executive Life — paper that Apollo really knew what it was. They knew the numbers.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: And Leon was a salesperson and a financier.</p><p> MORGENSON: He was the finance guy.</p><p>里索兹：对。</p><p> MORGENSON: And so, he knew the numbers. He knew the companies. And so, he knew that they were distressed and that they could be restructured and reorganized.</p><p>里索兹：对。</p><p> MORGENSON: And so, he buys this portfolio of junk bonds.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: So anyway, he&#39;s New York-based, right?</p><p> MORGENSON: He&#39;s New York-based.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: And executive life is in California.</p><p> MORGENSON: Yes, yes.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: But because of the relationship with Drexel, he approaches California and says, “We&#39;d like to buy this junk paper,” or did they hold an auction? How did it go?</p><p> MORGENSON: Well, it was with a French bank, actually. They were representing the bank. They were acting as the investment manager for the bank, and so it was going to be taken over by this French bank. But anyway, so the Department of Insurance sold it, sold the company on the cheap, absolutely.</p><p> And so, the people that bought it, in this case, the French bank and Apollo, were able to ride the recovery of those junk bonds.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: So, when California sells this, on behalf of the policyholders, is there any mandate, “Hey, you have to pay $0.90 on the dollar, at least,” or are there any requirements? They&#39;re selling it inexpensively. What riders is California attaching it to the new owners on behalf of the people the California insurance board is supposed to be operating on?</p><p> MORGENSON: Well, California, at the time, said, “We think this is a great deal. You&#39;re going to get at least $0.90 on the dollar. Everybody&#39;s going to get at least $0.90 on the dollar.” That is their story, and they&#39;re sticking to that.</p><p>里索兹：对。</p><p> MORGENSON: And that&#39;s what they say.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: But they didn&#39;t require that as part of the purchase.</p><p> MORGENSON: Well, that&#39;s what they said was going to happen as part of the purchase.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: I could say all sorts of things, but until I sign a contract that says, “I guarantee that I will pay 90 cents out to each shareholder at a minimum,” it&#39;s just words.</p><p> MORGENSON: Yes, well, what happened was, a lot of people did not get 90 cents on the dollar. There were quite a few people who were up in arms who wanted this to be investigated. It is sort of a moment in time that you look at and you say, “This is what can happen if an insurance company takes risks with their policyholder&#39;s money.”</p><p>里索兹：对。 This all goes back to the gunslinger as opposed to a conservative operator. There are a couple of other regulatory questions that come up that I&#39;m always sort of fascinated about. The first is the performance reporting for private equity. There have been lots of criticism from within Wall Street that at best it&#39;s aggressive, and at worst it&#39;s just a fantasy.</p><p> If you&#39;re committing capital to private equity, you don&#39;t care when they do the purchase. The sort of internal rate of return to the endowments and pensions who put money into private equity. They don&#39;t care about that, but that seems to be the way they report.</p><p> Tell us a little bit about how performance numbers are ginned up. I don&#39;t even know how to describe it.</p><p> MORGENSON: Well, these are private companies, not the firms themselves. They&#39;re publicly traded, as you know. But when they buy a company and put it into a fund, it&#39;s a private company. And so, how they mark the value of that company is, there&#39;s leeway there, Barry. They can value it a certain way that, let&#39;s just say, the stock market wouldn&#39;t value it at.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: But you&#39;re valuing it specifically how you&#39;re purchasing it, and then if it&#39;s sold five years later, that&#39;s a hard dollar. Why is there so much wiggle room in between?</p><p> MORGENSON: Because you haven&#39;t had a buyer tell you exactly what it&#39;s worth until the end of the line when you actually do buy the company.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: Really interesting. Let&#39;s talk about tax loopholes.</p><p> How on earth is there still a carried interest tax loophole for private equity, hedge funds, and venture capital? You&#39;re talking about a teeny, tiny fraction of all taxpayers. Why the special treatment?</p><p> MORGENSON: It started out, I think, as a special treatment for real estate, and it sort of morphed into this bigger thing as the private equity venture world expanded. And it essentially is that the managers, executives of these companies just end up paying a far, far lower rate on their very beneficent payouts than you or I do.</p><p> And it&#39;s a loophole that people have tried to get rid of for decades. We&#39;ve had congressional hearings about it. And yet it continues to stay on the books. And boy, they cry bloody murder when it comes time for people to say, look, maybe we should rethink this and not let these guys — I mean, it&#39;s like a billionaire minting machine to have this kind of a lower tax rate on these folks?</p><p> RITHOLTZ: Who wants to pay 37% when you could pay essentially 23%? Of course they&#39;re spending money on lobbyists. Cut my taxes in half, where do I sign up for that? Oh wait, I don&#39;t have access to that.</p><p> MORGENSON: Start a private equity firm, Barry.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: So here&#39;s what we&#39;ll do. We&#39;ll start a private equity firm, we&#39;ll buy pensions, and just put it in the S&amp;P 500 and cost us five BPs to manage it. There&#39;s a lot of fat there if you approach it that way.</p><p> So, let&#39;s talk about a little bit of pushback. I&#39;ve seen some criticisms and some stuff. I want to get your take on it.</p><p> First, we touched on this earlier. Aren&#39;t the big firms and the LBOs, the leveraged buyouts, very different than the middle market, smaller private equity firms that provide capital and equity to small companies. Aren&#39;t you painting with too broad a brush, goes some of the criticism?</p><p> MORGENSON: Well, if you look at these firms, these folks, these really titans of industry. celebrated in the business pages, they are, you know, on TV all the time. I mean, these are the people leading the way on this industry.</p><p> Now, again, there are others who are doing it right and doing it in a better way, yes.</p><p> But what you want to focus on, these are the folks that set the tone. These are the folks that say, “Here&#39;s how we&#39;re going to operate” and these are the folks that do have the biggest impact, Barry, because of their size. And so that&#39;s why we really want to focus on them.</p><p> So when you have two firms controlling 30% of emergency departments in this country.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: That&#39;s a lot.</p><p> MORGENSON: That&#39;s why you focus on the big firms. They have the big impact, and so that&#39;s why we&#39;re doing that.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: So let&#39;s talk about wealth inequality. You guys put a lot of blame on private equity for making it worse. But I look at wealth inequality and wage inequality, and it&#39;s a lot of things. It&#39;s low wages and a minimum wage that hasn&#39;t gone up in forever. It&#39;s corporate tax avoidance. It&#39;s the shifting of the tax burden away from the wealthy and away from corporations to the middle class.</p><p> Aren&#39;t we putting too much blame on private equity for exacerbating wealth inequality in America?</p><p> MORGENSON: Well, the reason we think it&#39;s important to include them in the mix is that we haven&#39;t really had that discussion. I mean, private equity was not really mentioned as a force in the inequality in the gulf between rich and poor in America. You would hear about offshoring of jobs, you would hear about companies going to Ireland so that they wouldn&#39;t have to pay the high taxes.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: The double Dutch whatever it&#39;s called thing.</p><p> MORGENSON: And so there has been a lot of discussion and of course the defanging or the diminishment of unions so you don&#39;t have a balance of power between the worker and the corporation. But you look at some of the forces behind those forces, right?</p><p> So pensions, great example. If you&#39;re starting to see private equity firms taking over pensions, you know, and or stripping the pensions of the companies that they bankrupt, that is a definite wealth gulf, right? That is a definite impact on everyday people, Main Street America, that I just don&#39;t think we&#39;ve really examined.</p><p> So you just have to look behind some of the practices.</p><p> When you have retailing, that&#39;s a big force, a big area that private equity has been very forceful in. Almost 600,000 jobs lost in retailing. Now, yes, some of that would have happened with the shift to online. But honestly, there have been consequences like that. So you look at that, and then you look at the problems with health care and what it&#39;s doing to patients. And so I do think that it is a force to be reckoned with here.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: So I&#39;m glad you brought up retail. Some of the pushback I&#39;ve seen is the United States has been wildly over-retailed. I think in 2007, we had 24 square feet per capita versus Europe, which was like 14, and Japan, which was like 9. So we really had far more retailers than we knew what to do.</p><p> We built way too many malls and ultimately, this was going to go through a huge set of changes.</p><p> Anyway, private equity may be an accelerator a little bit, but we certainly can&#39;t blame the shrinking retail footprint on PE, can we?</p><p> MORGENSON: We can maybe put some of it on them, right, yes. And obviously, the shift to online hurt some folks, Toys R Us is an example of that.</p><p>里索兹：对。 And more recently, Bed Bath &amp; Beyond, that was a publicly traded company.</p><p> MORGENSON: That&#39;s right.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: They hit the wall without private equity&#39;s help.</p><p> So the biggest pushback I&#39;ve seen is, go back to the &#39;80s and &#39;90s when LBOs were first ramping up, companies went from big to really big. And as these big publicly traded mega companies went upmarket, the banks, the brokers, all of Wall Street chased them, and they just created this air pocket, this void underneath where there used to be national banks and national lenders servicing that industry, and they have nobody left to service them. And that vacuum is into what good private equity has stepped.</p><p> If it wasn&#39;t for the private equity below the four biggest companies, there&#39;s very little sources of capital for these $100, $500, $700 million firms that Wall Street ignores.</p><p> MORGENSON: Well, I think you have to say, then, if you&#39;re going to say, “Okay, these companies are not being banked properly,” then that&#39;s great if you can get money from private equity. But let&#39;s not bankrupt them in the process. You have a study that shows that bankruptcies occur far more with companies that are private equitized than it does with other companies.</p><p> So I think that, yes, if you want to have the resources, the capital is not being assigned to these companies, but that doesn&#39;t mean that they should be abused or that some of these practices can&#39;t be questioned.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: And one of my favorite parts of the book, you talk about equity ownership and wealth ownership in the United States. In 1913, the bottom 90% of incomes owned about 15% of the wealth in the United States. This is real estate, businesses, and publicly traded companies. By the &#39;80s, that had more than doubled to 35% of the wealth in the US Was that the peak? What happened with that going forward?</p><p> MORGENSON: That was the peak. And one of the reasons for that very big considerable growth and that was the, you know, people were able to have a family without having two wage earners….</p><p>里索兹：对。</p><p> MORGENSON: You were able to buy a house, et cetera. That moment in time, also a huge contributor to that was pensions. So corporate pensions that gave a worker a reasonable shot at a prosperous retirement.</p><p> And those started disappearing in the mid to late &#39;80s. And so that&#39;s a big factor in why the wealth held by the Main Street America, the middle class, the big broad brush America. That&#39;s why that has declined.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: So here&#39;s, I think, my favorite pushback to the conversation about wealth inequality, and I&#39;m curious as to your thoughts. It&#39;s not the top 10% versus the bottom 90% where that big disparity has opened up. It&#39;s not even the top 1% versus the bottom 99%, although that&#39;s certainly pretty meaty.</p><p> It&#39;s the top 0.01% versus even within the top 1%, there&#39;s this massive disparity. We didn&#39;t used to have that many billionaires and uberwealthy today versus 50, 100 years ago. How has the distribution of wealth shifted in the United States and what might come out of that going forward?</p><p> MORGENSON: I just don&#39;t think it&#39;s a good thing to have this coterie of extreme, extreme wealth at the top of the pyramid. I mean, it&#39;s just not healthy. An economy does better if the most people are prosperous, right? And so these multi, multi, multi-billionaires are really outliers, but it points to a problem with the entire society.</p><p> And perhaps it&#39;s because we laud wealthy people, but part of it is this tax loophole that really is unfair. Part of it is some of the practices that really are aggressive and that end up harming companies and workers and pensioners. And let&#39;s not forget the huge fees that pensions pay to buy into private equity funds. And for years, those private equity funds outperformed the S&amp;P, but they no longer do.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: So let&#39;s hit on that, because that&#39;s really interesting. This was a small asset class that, whether it was the illiquidity premium or just the ability to go places where the public markets couldn&#39;t, actually did better than the markets.</p><p> That risk premia seems to have evaporated.</p><p> MORGENSON: It stopped outperforming in like the mid-2000s or towards 2008. And so you really have to wonder what the purpose of the continued infatuation with private equity among pensions is if they can get the same return in a S&amp;P 500 with five basis points as a cost.</p><p>里索兹：对。</p><p> MORGENSON: And total transparency, by the way, and a mark-to-market that you see at the end of every business day. And so, you know where you stand. So, it&#39;s not one of these fuzzy math situations where you don&#39;t really know what the value of the fund is because it&#39;s got private companies in it that are being marked by individuals who have an ax to grind in the mark.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: Really quite interesting.</p><p> So, let me give you one of my curveball questions I like to surprise guests with. Your career history is “Money Magazine” in the early, mid-18th Davies, and then “Forbes” and then “Worth” magazine. But while you were at “Forbes” in 1995, you get tapped to be press secretary for then presidential election candidate Steve Forbes? What was that like? How different are political campaigns from covering finance?</p><p> MORGENSON: Well, when Steve asked me to be his press secretary, I thought, “Wow, this this is going to be interesting. I even maybe thought this is going to be fun.</p><p>里索兹：对。</p><p> MORGENSON: Now I&#39;m a financial reporter, I am not a Washington reporter, I&#39;m not a political reporter, and so I had a different idea of what it might be like, but anyway, it was a very, very tough six months period.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: I can imagine.</p><p> MORGENSON: And it was, so Steve was a candidate that had economic ideas, okay?</p><p> RITHOLTZ: Flat tax, that was his big–</p><p> MORGENSON: One of them was the flat tax, which by the way would have gotten rid of lobbyists. That was the big benefit.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: And all those loopholes, right?</p><p> MORGENSON: Flat tax, he was also for medical savings accounts and health savings accounts. Anyway, and so I would explain these concepts. And he was against the double taxation of dividends, which of course we have gotten rid of, I think.</p><p> Anyway, so those were sort of three of his initial ideas. And I would have to explain these to the Washington Press Corps, the Washington Press Corps not being financially oriented and probably not that interested. They were just interested in the horse race.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: Always, even to this day.</p><p> MORGENSON: Now, he did very well in New Hampshire, and so for a frenzied moment, it was like, maybe he has a chance or a shot. But anyway, it was a very trying time for me, but I really became a better journalist because of it.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: I was going to go there with that question. What was it like being on the other side of the clamoring, that scrum that you always see the photos of? How did that change how you do journalism and view journalists?</p><p> MORGENSON: Well, I really, after that, decided that I really wanted to give people a lot more time to respond to my questions because I would be asked to answer questions that were quite comprehensive and/or tricky, difficult to come up with the answer in minutes.</p><p>里索兹：对。</p><p> MORGENSON: And so it was very frustrating to not be able to do that. And so I came away from that experience saying, okay, from now on, I&#39;m going to give everybody that I&#39;m writing about more time to respond because I don&#39;t want to put them in the situation that I was in.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: All right, we only have you for a few more minutes. Let me jump to my favorite questions that we ask all of our guests, starting with, tell us what you&#39;re streaming. What are you watching, listening to? What&#39;s keeping you entertained?</p><p> MORGENSON: What am I streaming? Well, gosh, I really like the BBC show “Happy Valley” I don&#39;t know if you&#39;ve seen that.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: No.</p><p> MORGENSON: It&#39;s kind of a detective, a pretty tough female detective, I like that. I like “Ted Lasso.”</p><p> RITHOLTZ: What&#39;s not to love?</p><p> MORGENSON: I know that&#39;s very mundane, but. So those are the two right now.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: Tell us about mentors. Who helped shape your career?</p><p> MORGENSON: Jim Michaels, who was the editor of “Forbes” magazine. He was a very tough, old newspaper reporter. He was at UPI, and he was the guy who broke the story of Gandhi&#39;s assassination. So really knew how to do that kind of reporting. But he took his expertise to business and really taught me how to look at businesses, analyze balance sheets, income statements, really do contrarian reporting. He was a guy who didn&#39;t want the conventional wisdom. He wanted to question the conventional wisdom.</p><p> He was very difficult, very irascible, very demanding, but you really learned a lot.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: Interesting. Let&#39;s talk about books. What are some of your favorites and what have you been reading recently?</p><p> MORGENSON: I like 19th century fiction. So Anthony Trollope, “The Way We Live Now” which is a really wonderful book about a tycoon who is sort of a scoundrel, who sells shares in a railroad company that doesn&#39;t really exist.</p><p> Anyway…</p><p> RITHOLTZ: Well, if you want the railroad to exist, that&#39;ll cost you more.</p><p>摩根森：是的。 Right now, I&#39;m actually reading a biography of Genghis Khan.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: Oh, which one?</p><p> MORGENSON: Jack Weatherford.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: I&#39;m not sure if that&#39;s the one I read, but it&#39;s amazing.</p><p> MORGENSON: Yes, and that&#39;s a guy who was kind of slimed as being this terrible marauder and everything. It&#39;s a different story altogether, so I&#39;m really enjoying that.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: Our last two questions. What sort of advice would you give to a recent college grad who is interested in a career in either investigative journalism or finance?</p><p> MORGENSON: Well, I would, of course, say go with investigative reporting because I think we need more of it in this country. I think we don&#39;t have as much as we need. We have seen newspapers hollowed out, of course.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: Closed down left and right.</p><p> MORGENSON: Closed down. We&#39;ve also seen that the costs associated with investigative reporting, it&#39;s not easy. It&#39;s not something that happens overnight. So it really is costly and we&#39;ve seen that fewer and fewer of those folks.</p><p> So I would say gung ho if you can get a job doing that, that it is going to be the most fun that you&#39;re going to have and also doing a service.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: And what do you know about the world of investigative reporting and finance today you wish you knew back in the early 80s when you were first getting started?</p><p> MORGENSON: Well, let&#39;s see. So what&#39;s about the world of finance that I wish I knew 30 years ago is that it isn&#39;t as hard as you think. That it isn&#39;t, you know, a lot of people come out of college if they&#39;re not a financial person, like I was a humanities major, you know, and you have this mental block about numbers, I can&#39;t do numbers, or I, you know, it&#39;s not that hard. It really isn&#39;t that hard, it&#39;s common sense.</p><p> Now there are people who are really extra special good at it but, you know, it&#39;s something that you can tackle. Don&#39;t feel like you have a mental block against finance and don&#39;t think that finance isn&#39;t important. Finance is not a backwater, it touches everyone. It touches everybody in this country. It is political. It is everywhere. And so just don&#39;t discount the importance of finance. –</p><p> RITHOLTZ: Really interesting. Thank you, Gretchen, for being so generous with your time.</p><p> We have been speaking with Gretchen Morgenson. She is the author of “These Are the Plunderers, How Private Equity Runs and Wrecks America.”</p><p> If you enjoy this conversation, well, be sure and check out any of the previous 500 we&#39;ve done over the past, I don&#39;t know, eight years. You can find those on YouTube, iTunes, Spotify, or wherever you find your favorite podcasts.</p><p> Sign up for my daily reading list at ritholtz.com. Follow me on Twitter @Ritholtz. Follow all of the Bloomberg family of podcasts @podcast.</p><p> I would be remiss if I did not thank the crack team that helps put these conversations together each week. Sara Livezey is my audio engineer. Atika Valbrun is my project manager. Paris Wald is my producer. Sean Russo is my researcher. I&#39;m Barry Ritholtz, you&#39;ve been listening to Masters in Business on Bloomberg Radio.</p><p> END</p><p></p><p style="text-align: center;"> ~~~ </p><p></p><p><iframe style="width: 100%; max-width: 660px; overflow: hidden; background: transparent;" src="https://embed.podcasts.apple.com/us/podcast/masters-in-business/id730188152" height="450" frameborder="0" sandbox="allow-forms allow-popups allow-same-origin allow-scripts allow-storage-access-by-user-activation allow-top-navigation-by-user-activation" data-mce-fragment="1"></iframe></p><p><a rel="nofollow" href="https://ritholtz.com/2023/06/transcript-gretchen-morgenson/">后记：格雷琴·摩根森</a>首先出现在<a rel="nofollow" href="https://ritholtz.com">《大图片》</a>上。</p> ;
